\paragraph{Pathophysiology}
The disease is caused by twenty of the 30 species of the identified group of bacteria (in 1991\cite{nguyen1991legionellosis}), now more than 60 spices have been identified\textbf{TO CITE}.

\paragraph{Epidemiology}
Frequency of legionella pneumophila bacterium for community-acquired pneumonia is 0.5 to 10\%\footnote{it is a statistic that varies a lot depending on location and population criteria mainly}.

\subsection{Legionella pneumophila}
The legionella pneumophila is the primary humanpathogenic bacterium ([it] represents 80\% bacteria that cause legionellosis \textbf{CITE}) in this group and the causative agent of Legionnaires' disease\cite{nguyen1991legionellosis} (other name of Legionellosis disease). This bacteira is thin, aerobic, pleomorphic, flagellated, non-spore forming and gram-negative bacterium of the genus Legionella.

\paragraph{Bacteria location}
The bacterium is found naturally in fresh water. It can also contaminate hot water tanks, cooling towers. 

\paragraph{Detection}
The bacteria can be detected by immunofluorescence techiques. A fluorescent marker antibody come attach to the bacteria. This is a technique called indirect fluorescent antibody. Other tests like ELISA and microagglutination tests may be applied.\\
For clinical use, the appearance of simple diagnostic in urine tests has favored the search for specific antigens. It helped a lot in cluster discovery. Indeed, if there are much cases of legionellosis, there must be a source of bacteria somewhere near.

\paragraph{Biophysiology}
Legionella pneumophilia is a facultative intracellular parasite that can invade and replicate inside amoebae (a biological organism which has ability to alter its shape by extending and retracting pseudopods). Legionella pneumophilia bacteria uses these biological as reservoirs. They provide protection from stress from the environnement (e.g. chlorination of water, temperature).

\paragraph{Proliferation} 
The bacteria has ability to proliferate on the walls of pipes (biofilms). L. pneumophilia can be aerolized throught showers, sprinklers and other fixtures which may leads to to infection (after prolonged exposure). When aerolized in mist aire, the bacteria can spread too.

\paragraph{Statistics}
This bacteria is the cause agent for most of the legionellosis disease. In the USA, there are approximately 3 infections with L. pneumophilia for 100 000 peoples each years. There are a peak in the summer. In endemic regions (regions where legionellosis disease is more present) about 4\% to 5\%. In France, in 2005, the compulsory declaration took into account 1527 cases of legionellosis representing 2 cases per 100,000 inhabitants\footnote{Which is similar to USA statistics}. On the next figure, you can see the distribution of legionnaires' disease in Europe.
